03843nam a22006375i 9780292796652DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927966527 a10.7560/7094232doi  a(DE-B1597)588321  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN1995.9.A73bF46 2006eb 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/6572221 aFelleman, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArt in the Cinematic Imagination /cSusan Felleman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Baring the Device -- tCHAPTER 1 The Moving Picture Gallery -- tCHAPTER 2 A Form of Necrophilia (The Moving Picture Gallery Revisited) -- tCHAPTER 3 The Birth, Death, and Apotheosis of a Hollywood Love Goddess -- tCHAPTER 4 Survivors of the Shipwreck of Modernity -- tCHAPTER 5 Out of Her Element -- tCHAPTER 6 Playing with Fire -- tCHAPTER 7 Dirty Pictures, Mud Lust, and Abject Desire: Myths of Origin and the Cinematic Object -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing an art historical perspective to the realm of American and European film, Art in the Cinematic Imagination examines the ways in which films have used works of art and artists themselves as cinematic and narrative motifs. From the use of portraits in Vertigo to the cinematic depiction of women artists in Artemisia and Camille Claudel, Susan Felleman incorporates feminist and psychoanalytic criticism to reveal individual and collective perspectives on sex, gender, identity, commerce, and class. Probing more than twenty films from the postwar era through contemporary times, Art in the Cinematic Imagination considers a range of structurally significant art objects, artist characters, and art-world settings to explore how the medium of film can amplify, reinvent, or recontextualize the other visual arts. Fluently speaking across disciplines, Felleman's study brings a broad array of methodologies to bear on questions such as the evolution of the "Hollywood Love Goddess" and the pairing of the feminine with death on screen. A persuasive approach to an engaging body of films, Art in the Cinematic Imagination illuminates a compelling and significant facet of the cinematic experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArt and motion pictures. 0aArt in motion pictures. 0aArtists in motion pictures. 0aWomen in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796652423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796652/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK